<br>
1.  No one has a right to NOT be offended.<br>
2.  No one has the right to tell me what I can and cannot say.<br>
3.  Moderators have the right to ban me for my speech if it is vulgar (i.e., widely considered, in the language in which it is written, to be profanity)<br>
4.  Moderators have the right to ban me if my tie is out of style.<br>
6.  There is no number 5.<br>
<br>
Having said that:<br>
<br>
a)  The word Nazi was a shortened version (nickname if you will) for the Nationalist Socialist party in Germany.<br>
b)  In that respect, it is no more vulgar than calling someone a Democrat or Republican<br>
c)  Objection to the actions that some perpetrated is entirely different than objection to a symbol... ergo, one can disagree with the practice of slavery and still fly the Confederate Flag.<br>
d)  In the vernacular, the term 'nazi' has gained the stigmata of 'enforced zealotry'.  While this is not the original meaning of the term, it reflects the meaning the term came to represent considering the actions of those who acted under its banner.<br>
f)  There is no 'e'.<br>
<br>
An excellent example of this would be the Seinfeld episode, 'Soup Nazi'.  Indeed, this episode help to propel the word to it's current use in the vernacular.<br>
<br>
Thus, if I or anyone else chooses to use the word 'Nazi' then we're going to use it.  It is not considered vulgar in common useage, although any member of this board may consider it's use vulgar as a personal belief.  Then again, some may consider the use of the term 'Democrat' or 'Fat Hippy Boy' or 'meat' vulgar.  They have their right to object, however they do not have the right to censor my speech.<br>
<br>
That being said, I will endeavor to speak in such terms as are appropriate for the subject.  But if I feel that the word 'Nazi' carries the meaning I wish to convey, I will use it.<br>
<br>
As an aside, the Nazi's bombed the living schmoozola out of my family in London during WWII.  I have no love of their movement.  But I abhor the PC movement even more.<br>
